        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1969-08-20T13:10:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1969-08-20T13:10:00-05:00" n="98"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d98">
                <head>98. Memorandum of Conversation<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d98fn1"
                        >Source: National Archives, Nixon Presidential Materials, <gloss
                            target="#t_NSC_1">NSC</gloss> Files, Box 670, Country Files—Europe,
                        Canada, Vol. I. Secret. The meeting took place in the President’s office in
                        the Western White House. An attached August 26 note indicates <persName
                            corresp="#p_HAM_1">Haig</persName> was the drafting officer.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>San Clemente</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            type="conversation-or-meeting-date" when="1969-08-20T11:10:00-07:00"
                            >August 20, 1969, 11:10 a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Memorandum of Conversation between President <persName corresp="#p_NRM_1"
                            >Nixon</persName> and Departing Ambassadors to Australia, Barbados,
                        Canada, Iceland, Peru and Romania</item>
                </list>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>PARTICIPANTS</head>
                    <item>President <persName corresp="#p_NRM_1">Richard Nixon</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Ambassador Walter L. Rice, Australia</item>
                    <item>Ambassador Eileen Donovan, Barbados</item>
                    <item>Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_SA_1">Adolph W. Schmidt</persName>,
                        Canada</item>
                    <item>Ambassador Luther I. Replogle, Iceland</item>
                    <item>Ambassador Taylor G. Belcher, Peru</item>
                    <item>Ambassador Leonard C. Meeker, Romania</item>
                    <item>Colonel <persName corresp="#p_HAM_1">Alexander M. Haig</persName>, <gloss
                            target="#t_NSC_1">NSC</gloss>
                    </item>
                    <item>Mr. Nicholas Ruwe (Made introductions and departed during substantive
                        discussions)</item>
                </list>
                <p>After introductions, the President invited the newly appointed Ambassadors to sit
                    down in his office and proceeded to review the situation in each of the
                    countries to which the Ambassadors have been designated.</p>
                <p rend="sectiontitleital">Canada</p>
                <p>The President stated that the Ambassadorial challenge in Canada was an exciting
                    one at this point in the history of that country. He noted that the Canadians,
                    although fully cognizant of their economic and industrial dependence upon the
                    United States, are nevertheless increasingly manifesting a degree of
                    independence not heretofore demonstrated. He suggested that our Ambassador would
                    have to be particularly careful about Canadian-<gloss target="#t_NATO_1"
                        >NATO</gloss> relationships emphasizing that Canada’s actions and attitudes
                    could have an influence on the attitudes of the other members of the Alliance.
                    Thus it became important for the United States to attempt to influence Canada’s
                    attitudes toward <gloss target="#t_NATO_1">NATO</gloss>. The President noted
                    that Prime Minister <persName corresp="#p_TPE_1">Trudeau</persName> might
                    present special problems to the Ambassador because he was at times erratic with
                    many of the characteristics so frequently associated with intellectuals. The
                    President encouraged Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_SA_1">Schmidt</persName>
                    to establish effective relationships with levels of the Canadian Government just
                        <pb facs="0438" n="399" xml:id="pg_399"/> below the Prime Minister to
                    increase his own assets for influencing the Prime Minister.<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d98fn2">The President announced Ambassador <persName
                            corresp="#p_SA_1">Adolph Schmidt</persName>’s appointment on July 8.
                            <persName corresp="#p_SA_1">Schmidt</persName> presented his credentials
                        on September 11. Regarding the choice of <persName corresp="#p_LH_1"
                            >Linder</persName>’s successor, see <hi rend="italic">
                            <persName corresp="#p_HHR_1">Haldeman</persName> Diaries: Multimedia
                            Edition,</hi> March 12, 1969.</note>
                </p>
                <p>[Omitted here is material unrelated to Canada.]</p>
            </div>
